Idiomatic Rust would probably avoid allocations, which means something more like<p><pre><code>    fn main() {
        if let Some(arg) = std::env::args().nth(1) {
            println!(&quot;{}&quot;, {
                match arg.char_indices().nth(12) {
                    Some((idx, _)) => &arg[..idx],
                    None => &*arg
                }
            });
        }
    }
</code></pre>
With the `unicode-segmentation` crate[1], you can just swap `char_indices()` with `grapheme_indices(true)`.<p>[1] <a href="https://crates.io/crates/unicode-segmentation" rel="nofollow">https://crates.io/crates/unicode-segmentation</a>
